  "prompt": "What can cause astigmatism?",
  "response": "Astigmatism is a common vision condition that occurs when the cornea (the clear front surface of the eye) or the lens inside the eye has an irregular shape. Instead of being perfectly spherical, the cornea or lens is more oval or football-shaped, causing light to focus unevenly on the retina, which leads to blurred or distorted vision. The exact cause of astigmatism is often unknown, but several factors can contribute to its development:\n\n### 1. **Congenital (Present at Birth)**\n   - Astigmatism is often hereditary and can be present from birth. It may be related to the shape of the cornea or lens inherited from parents.\n   - Many babies are born with some degree of astigmatism, which may improve or worsen as they grow.\n\n### 2. **Corneal Shape Irregularities**\n   - The cornea is normally round, but in astigmatism, it has a more oblong shape. This irregular curvature can cause light to refract unevenly.\n   - Conditions like **keratoconus** (a progressive thinning and bulging of the cornea) can lead to astigmatism.\n\n### 3. **Lens Irregularities**\n   - Astigmatism can also occur if the lens inside the eye has an irregular shape, known as **lenticular astigmatism**.\n\n### 4. **Eye Surgery or Injury**\n   - Trauma to the eye, such as a scratch or injury, can alter the shape of the cornea and cause astigmatism.\n   - Certain types of eye surgery, like cataract surgery or corneal transplants, can also lead to astigmatism if the cornea heals unevenly.\n\n### 5. **Eye Diseases or Infections**\n   - Conditions like corneal scarring, swelling, or infections can alter the shape of the cornea and contribute to astigmatism.\n\n### 6. **Developmental Changes**\n   - Astigmatism can develop or worsen during childhood or adolescence as the eyes grow and change shape.\n\n### 7. **Environmental Factors**\n   - Prolonged or excessive eye strain, such as reading in poor light or extensive screen time, may contribute to astigmatism in some cases, though this is less common.\n\n### 8. **Other Health Conditions**\n   - Certain systemic conditions, such as diabetes, can affect the shape of the lens or cornea and lead to astigmatism.\n\n### Common Symptoms of Astigmatism\n   - Blurred or distorted vision at all distances\n   - Eyestrain or discomfort\n   - Headaches\n   - Difficulty with night vision\n   - Squinting\n\n### Treatment Options\nAstigmatism can be corrected with:\n   - **Eyeglasses** or **contact lenses** (toric lenses)\n   - **Refractive surgery**, such as LASIK or PRK\n   - Orthokeratology (corneal reshaping lenses worn overnight)\n\nIf you suspect you have astigmatism, consult an eye care professional for a comprehensive eye exam and appropriate treatment.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
